Summary of the Post
The post explains the Chandrasekhar limit (~1.4 solar masses). It describes how white dwarfs are supported against gravitational collapse by electron degeneracy pressure (a quantum mechanical effect rooted in the Pauli exclusion principle). Once a white dwarf exceeds this mass limit, the electrons can no longer resist gravity effectively (especially when moving near the speed of light), leading to collapse into a neutron star or black hole, often triggering a supernova.
This is a well-established result in astrophysics from the 1930s.
